Vertical profiles generated bioRad vol2bird algorithm, originally developed single dual-polarization C-band radars (Dokter et al.¬†2011). underlying C-code algorithm refactored compatibility European US radar formats, improved structure readability code base. code: # make sure you start with a fresh R session # load the bioRad package library(bioRad) # check the package version packageVersion("bioRad") # bring up the package general help page: ?bioRad # make a new local directory on your machine for this practical # replace the string below with the path of that directory: HOME <- "your/personal/working/directory/" # check that the directory exists. If the next statement evaluates to FALSE, something went wrong: the directory does not exist or you didn't specify its path correctly file.exists(HOME) # we will make HOME our work directory, the default folder in which R will look # for files, and where it will output newly generated files. setwd(HOME) # next, we will create two directories where we will be storing data: dir.create("./data_vpts") # here we will store vertical profile time series (vpts data) dir.create("./data_pvol") # here we will store polar volumes (pvol data) # Finally, we set the local time zone to UTC, so all plotted time axes will be in UTC Sys.setenv(TZ = "UTC")

code: # Let's continue with the vpts object created in the previous example. # The vertically integrated quantities are calculated as follows: my_vpi <- integrate_profile(my_vpts) # The my_vpi object you created is a vpi class object, which is an acronym for "vertical profile integrated". It has its own plot method, which by default plots migration traffic rate (MTR): plot(my_vpi) # you can also plot vertically integrated densities (VID): plot(my_vpi, quantity = "vid") # the gray and white shading indicates day and night, which is calculated # from the date and the radar position. You can also turn this off: plot(my_vpi, night_shade = FALSE) # plot the cumulative number of birds passing the radar, i.e. migration traffic (mt): plot(my_vpi, quantity = "mt") # execute `?plot.vpi` to open the help page listing all the options. ?plot.vpi # instead of vertically integrated density (VID), you can use vertically integrated reflectivity (VIR): plot(my_vpi, quantity = "vir") # instead of migration traffic rate (MTR), you can use the reflectivity traffic rate (RTR): plot(my_vpi, quantity = "rtr") # instead of migration traffic (MT), you can use the reflectivity traffic (RT): plot(my_vpi, quantity = "rt")

title: Apply MistNet segmentation to a polar volume ‚Äî apply_mistnet
text: MistNet (Lin et al. 2019) deep convolutional neural network trained using labels derived S-band dual-polarization data across US NEXRAD network. purpose screen areas precipitation weather radar data, primarily legacy data dual-polarization data available. network trained S-band data, may perform well C-band. MistNet requires three single-polarization parameters input: reflectivity (DBZH), radial velocity (VRADH), spectrum width (WRADH), 5 specific elevation angles (0.5, 1.5, 2.5, 3.5 4.5 degrees). Based data can estimate segmentation mask identifies pixels weather removed interested biological data . MistNet calculate three class probabilities (0 1, 1 corresponding 100% probability) additional scan parameters polar volume: BACKGROUND: Class probability signal detected noise level radar. WEATHER: Class probability weather detected. BIOLOGY: Class probability biological scatterers detected. MistNet calculate three class probabilities (0 1, 1 corresponding 100% probability) additional scan parameters polar volume: BACKGROUND: Class probability signal detected noise level radar WEATHER: Class probability weather detected BIOLOGY: Class probability biological scatterers detected class probabilities available 5 input elevations used input MistNet model. Based class probabilities final weather segmentation map calculated, stored scan parameter CELL, available elevation scans. CELL: Final weather segmentation, values > 1 indicating pixels classified weather values equal 1 indicating pixels located within 5 km distance weather pixels. pixel classified weather class probability WEATHER > 0.45 average class probability rain across five MistNet elevation scans spatial location > 0.45. code: # Locate and read the polar volume example file pvolfile <- system.file("extdata", "volume.h5", package = "bioRad") pvol <- read_pvolfile(pvolfile)  # Calculate linear reflectivity ETA from reflectivity factor DBZH radar_wavelength <- pvol$attributes$how$wavelength pvol <- calculate_param(pvol, ETA = dbz_to_eta(DBZH, radar_wavelength)) #> Error in eval(nn <- (calc[[i]]), x$params): object 'radar_wavelength' not found  # Add depolarization ratio (DR) as a scan parameter (see Kilambi 2018) pvol <- calculate_param(pvol, DR = 10 * log10((ZDR + 1 - 2 * ZDR^0.5 * RHOHV) /   (ZDR + 1 + 2 * ZDR^0.5 * RHOHV)))  # The function also works on scan and ppi objects calculate_param(example_scan, DR = 10 * log10((ZDR + 1 - 2 * ZDR^0.5 * RHOHV) /   (ZDR + 1 + 2 * ZDR^0.5 * RHOHV))) #>                   Polar scan (class scan) #>  #>      parameters:  DBZH VRADH RHOHV ZDR PHIDP DR  #> elevation angle:  0.5 deg #>            dims:  480 bins x 360 rays  # set all reflectivity  values to NA when correlation coefficient > 0.95 # (indicating precipitation) if (require(dplyr, quietly = TRUE)) {   calculate_param(pvol,     DBZH=if_else(c(RHOHV)>.95, NA, c(DBZH)) ) } #>  #> Attaching package: ‚Äòdplyr‚Äô #> The following objects are masked from ‚Äòpackage:stats‚Äô: #>  #>     filter, lag #> The following objects are masked from ‚Äòpackage:base‚Äô: #>  #>     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union #>                Polar volume (class pvol) #>  #>      # scans:  3  #>        radar:  seang  #>       source:  WMO:02606,RAD:SE50,PLC:Angelholm,NOD:seang,ORG:82,CTY:643,CMT:Swedish radar  #> nominal time:  2015-10-18 18:00:00  #>   # it also works for ppis ppi <- project_as_ppi(example_scan) calculate_param(ppi, exp(DBZH)) #>                Plan position indicator (class ppi) #>  #>   parameters:  DBZH VRADH RHOHV ZDR PHIDP exp(DBZH)  #>         dims:  201 x 201 pixels #>

text: Calculates vertical profile biological scatterers (vp) polar volume (pvol) file using algorithm vol2bird (Dokter et al. 2011 doi:10.1098/rsif.2010.0116 ).

title: Calculate a vertical profile (vp) from a polar volume (pvol) file ‚Äî calculate_vp
code: calculate_vp(   file,   vpfile = "",   pvolfile_out = "",   autoconf = FALSE,   verbose = FALSE,   warnings = TRUE,   mount,   sd_vvp_threshold,   rcs = 11,   dual_pol = TRUE,   rho_hv = 0.95,   single_pol = TRUE,   elev_min = 0,   elev_max = 90,   azim_min = 0,   azim_max = 360,   range_min = 5000,   range_max = 35000,   n_layer = 20,   h_layer = 200,   dealias = TRUE,   nyquist_min = if (dealias) 5 else 25,   dbz_quantity = "DBZH",   mistnet = FALSE,   mistnet_elevations = c(0.5, 1.5, 2.5, 3.5, 4.5),   local_install,   local_mistnet )

title: Calculate a vertical profile (vp) from a polar volume (pvol) file ‚Äî calculate_vp
text: file Character (vector). Either path single radar polar volume (pvol) file containing multiple scans/sweeps, multiple paths scan files containing single scan/sweep. single pvol object. file data format either 1) ODIM format, implementation OPERA data information model HDF5 format, 2) format supported RSL library 3) Vaisala IRIS (IRIS RAW) format. vpfile Character. File name. provided, writes vertical profile file (vpfile) either VPTS CSV ODIM HDF5 format disk. pvolfile_out Character. File name. provided, writes polar volume (pvol) file ODIM HDF5 format disk. Useful converting RSL formats ODIM. autoconf Logical. TRUE, default optimal configuration settings selected automatically user settings ignored. verbose Logical. TRUE, vol2bird stdout piped R console. warnings Logical. TRUE, vol2bird warnings piped R console. mount Character. Directory path mount point Docker container (deprecated). sd_vvp_threshold Numeric. Lower threshold radial velocity standard deviation (profile quantity sd_vvp) m/s. Biological signals sd_vvp < sd_vvp_threshold set zero. Defaults 2 m/s C-band radars 1 m/s S-band radars. rcs Numeric. Radar cross section per bird use, cm^2. dual_pol Logical. TRUE, uses dual-pol mode, meteorological echoes filtered using correlation coefficient threshold rho_hv. rho_hv Numeric. Lower threshold correlation coefficient use filtering meteorological scattering. single_pol Logical. TRUE, uses precipitation filtering single polarization mode based reflectivity radial velocity quantities. elev_min Numeric. Minimum elevation angle include, degrees. elev_max Numeric. Maximum elevation angle include, degrees. azim_min Numeric. Minimum azimuth include, degrees clockwise north. azim_max Numeric. Maximum azimuth include, degrees clockwise north. range_min Numeric. Minimum range include, m. range_max Numeric. Maximum range include, m. n_layer Numeric. Number altitude layers use generated profile. h_layer Numeric. Width altitude layers use generated profile, m. dealias Logical. Whether dealias radial velocities. typically done scans polar volume low Nyquist velocities (25 m/s). nyquist_min Numeric. Minimum Nyquist velocity scans include, m/s. dbz_quantity Name available reflectivity factor use DBZH (e.g. DBZV, TH, TV). mistnet Logical. Whether use MistNet segmentation model. mistnet_elevations Numeric vector length 5. Elevation angles feed MistNet segmentation model, expects exactly 5 elevation scans 0.5, 1.5, 2.5, 3.5 4.5 degrees. Specifying different elevation angles may compromise segmentation results. local_install Character. Path local vol2bird installation (e.g. /vol2bird_install_directory/vol2bird/bin/vol2bird.sh). (deprecated) local_mistnet Character. Path local MistNet segmentation model PyTorch format (e.g. //path/mistnet_nexrad.pt).

title: Calculate a vertical profile (vp) from a polar volume (pvol) file ‚Äî calculate_vp
code: # Locate and read the polar volume example file pvolfile_source <- system.file("extdata", "volume.h5", package = "bioRad")  # Copy the file to a temporary directory with read/write permissions pvolfile <- paste0(tempdir(),"/volume.h5") file.copy(pvolfile_source, pvolfile) #> [1] TRUE  # Calculate the profile if (requireNamespace("vol2birdR", quietly = TRUE)) { vp <- calculate_vp(pvolfile)  # Get summary info vp  # Clean up file.remove(pvolfile)  } #> Running vol2birdSetUp #> Warning: radial velocities will be dealiased... #> [1] TRUE

title: Vertically integrate profiles (vp or vpts) into an integrated profile (vpi) ‚Äî integrate_profile
text: function generates specially classed data frame following quantities: datetime: POSIXct date profile UTC vid: Vertically Integrated Density individuals/km^2. vid surface density, whereas dens vp objects volume density. vir: Vertically Integrated Reflectivity cm^2/km^2 mtr: Migration Traffic Rate individuals/km/h rtr: Reflectivity Traffic Rate cm^2/km/h mt: Migration Traffic individuals/km, cumulated start time series datetime rt: Reflectivity Traffic cm^2/km, cumulated start time series datetime ff: Horizontal ground speed m/s dd: Direction horizontal ground speed degrees u: Ground speed component west east m/s v: Ground speed component south north m/s height: Mean flight height (height weighted eta) m sea level Vertically integrated density reflectivity related according \(vid=vir/rcs(x)\), rcs assumed radar cross section per individual. Similarly, migration traffic rate reflectivity traffic rate related according \(mtr=rtr/rcs(x)\)

what: Migration traffic rate (mtr) and reflectivity traffic rate (rtr)
title: Vertically integrate profiles (vp or vpts) into an integrated profile (vpi) ‚Äî integrate_profile
text: Migration traffic rate (mtr) altitude layer flux measure, defined number targets crossing unit transect per hour. Column mtr output dataframe gives migration traffic rates individuals/km/hour. transect direction set angle alpha. alpha=NA, transect runs perpendicular measured migratory direction. mtr equals number crossing targets per km transect per hour, transect kept perpendicular measured migratory movement times altitudes. case mtr always positive quantity, defined : $$mtr = 3.6 \sum_i \mathit{dens}_i \mathit{ff}_i \Delta h$$ sum running altitude layers alt_min alt_max, \(\mathit{dens}_i\) bird density, \(\mathit{ff}_i\) ground speed altitude layer , \(\Delta h\) altitude layer width. factor 3.6 refers unit conversion speeds \(\mathit{ff}_i\) m/s km/h. alpha given numeric value, transect taken perpendicular direction alpha, number crossing targets per hour per km transect calculated : $$mtr = 3.6 \sum_i \mathit{dens}_i \mathit{ff}_i \cos((dd_i-\alpha) \pi/180) \Delta h$$ \(dd_i\) migratory direction altitude . Note equation evaluates previous equation alpha equals \(dd_i\). Also note can rewrite equation using trigonometry : $$mtr = 3.6 \sum_i \mathit{dens}_i (u_i \sin(\alpha \pi/180) + v_i \cos(\alpha \pi/180)) \Delta h$$ \(u_i\) \(v_i\) u v ground speed components altitude . definition mtr traditional flux direction interest. Targets moving direction alpha contribute positively mtr, targets moving opposite direction contribute negatively mtr. Therefore mtr can positive negative, depending definition alpha. Note mtr given value alpha can also calculated vertically integrated density vid height-integrated velocity components u v follows: $$mtr = 3.6 (u \sin(\alpha \pi/180) + v \cos(\alpha \pi/180)) vid$$ Formula reflectivity traffic rate rtr found replacing dens eta vid vir formula mtr. Reflectivity traffic rate gives cross-sectional area passing radar per km transect perpendicular migratory direction per hour. mtr values conditional settings rcs, rtr values .

title: Vertically integrate profiles (vp or vpts) into an integrated profile (vpi) ‚Äî integrate_profile
text: Migration traffic calculated time-integration migration traffic rates. Migration traffic gives number individuals passed per km perpendicular migratory direction position radar full period time series within specified altitude band. Reflectivity traffic calculated time-integration reflectivity traffic rates. Reflectivity traffic gives total cross-sectional area passed per km perpendicular migratory direction position radar full period time series within specified altitude band. mt values conditional settings rcs, rt values . Columns mt rt output dataframe provides migration traffic numeric value equal migration traffic reflectivity traffic start time series till moment time stamp respective row. Note \(\mathit{ff}_i=\sqrt(u_i^2 + v_i^2)\), hold height-integrated speeds, .e. \(\mathit{ff} \neq \sqrt(u^2 + v^2)\) soon ground speed directions vary altitude.

what: Ground speed (ff) and ground speed components (u,v)
title: Vertically integrate profiles (vp or vpts) into an integrated profile (vpi) ‚Äî integrate_profile
text: height-averaged ground speed defined : $$\mathit{ff} = \sum_i \mathit{dens}_i \mathit{ff}_i / \sum_i \mathit{dens}_i$$ sum running altitude layers alt_min alt_max, \(\mathit{dens}_i\) bird density, \(\mathit{ff}_i\) ground speed altitude layer . height-averaged u component (west east) defined : $$u = \sum_i \mathit{dens}_i u_i / \sum_i \mathit{dens}_i$$ height-averaged v component (south north) defined : $$v = \sum_i \mathit{dens}_i v_i / \sum_i \mathit{dens}_i$$

title: Calculate a plan position indicator (ppi) of vertically integrated density adjusted for range effects ‚Äî integrate_to_ppi
code: # \donttest{ # Locate and read the polar volume example file pvolfile <- system.file("extdata", "volume.h5", package = "bioRad")  # load polar volume pvol <- read_pvolfile(pvolfile)  # Read the corresponding vertical profile example data(example_vp)  # Calculate the range-corrected ppi on a 50x50 pixel raster ppi <- integrate_to_ppi(pvol, example_vp, nx = 50, ny = 50)  # Plot the vertically integrated reflectivity (VIR) using a # 0-2000 cm^2/km^2 color scale plot(ppi, zlim = c(0, 2000))   # Calculate the range-corrected ppi on finer 2000m x 2000m pixel raster ppi <- integrate_to_ppi(pvol, example_vp, res = 2000)  # Plot the vertically integrated density (VID) using a # 0-200 birds/km^2 color scale plot(ppi, param = "VID", zlim = c(0, 200))   # Download a basemap and map the ppi if (all(sapply(c("ggspatial","prettymapr", "rosm"), requireNamespace, quietly = TRUE))) { map(ppi) } #> Zoom: 5 #> Fetching 4 missing tiles #>    |                                                                               |                                                                      |   0%   |                                                                               |==================                                                    |  25%   |                                                                               |===================================                                   |  50%   |                                                                               |====================================================                  |  75%   |                                                                               |======================================================================| 100% #> ...complete!   # The ppi can also be projected on a user-defined raster, as follows:  # First define the raster template_raster <- raster::raster(   raster::extent(12, 13, 56, 57),   crs = sp::CRS("+proj=longlat") )  # Project the ppi on the defined raster ppi <- integrate_to_ppi(pvol, example_vp, raster = template_raster)  # Extract the raster data from the ppi object raster::brick(ppi$data) #> class      : RasterBrick  #> dimensions : 10, 10, 100, 6  (nrow, ncol, ncell, nlayers) #> resolution : 0.1, 0.1  (x, y) #> extent     : 12, 13, 56, 57  (xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax) #> crs        : +proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +no_defs  #> source     : memory #> names      :          VIR,          VID,            R,      overlap,      eta_sum, eta_sum_expected  #> min values :    0.0000000,    0.0000000,    0.0000000,    0.3189387,    0.0000000,      406.9671616  #> max values : 6.507961e+04, 5.892510e+03, 6.614504e+01, 9.217694e-01, 6.955712e+04,     3.196694e+03  #>   # Calculate the range-corrected ppi on an even finer 500m x 500m pixel raster, # cropping the area up to 50000 meter from the radar ppi <- integrate_to_ppi(   pvol, example_vp, res = 500,   xlim = c(-50000, 50000), ylim = c(-50000, 50000) ) plot(ppi, param = "VID", zlim = c(0, 200))  # }

Use 'regularize_vpts' to make time series regular.  # plot total reflectivity factor (rain, birds, insects together): plot(ts[1:500], ylim = c(0, 3000), quantity = "DBZH") #> Warning: Irregular time-series: missing profiles will not be visible. Use 'regularize_vpts' to make time series regular.  # regularize the time grid, which includes empty (NA) profiles at # time steps without data: ts_regular <- regularize_vpts(ts) #> projecting on 300 seconds interval grid... plot(ts_regular)  # change the color of missing NA data to red plot(ts_regular, na_color="red")  # change the color palette: plot(ts_regular[1:1000], ylim = c(0, 3000), palette=viridis::viridis(1000))  # change and inverse the color palette: plot(ts_regular[1:1000], ylim = c(0, 3000), palette=rev(viridis::viridis(1000, option="A")))  # plot the speed profile: plot(ts_regular[1:1000], quantity="ff")  # plot the northward speed component: plot(ts_regular[1:1000], quantity="v")  # plot speed profile with more legend ticks, plot(ts_regular[1:1000], quantity="ff", legend_ticks=seq(0,20,2), zlim=c(0,20))

title: Regularize a time series of vertical profiles (vpts) on a regular time grid ‚Äî regularize_vpts
text: ts object inheriting class vpts, see vpts() details. interval Time interval grid project . 'auto' median interval time series used. date_min Start time projected time series, POSIXct object. Taken ts default'. date_max End time projected time series, POSIXct object. Taken ts default. units Optional units interval fill, one 'secs', 'mins', 'hours','days', 'weeks'. Defaults 'mins'. fill Numeric Logical. fill regularized timestep closest original profile found within time window +/- fill. TRUE, fill maps interval, filling single missing timesteps. FALSE, fill  maps 0, disabling filling. verbose Logical, TRUE prints text console. keep_datetime Logical, TRUE keep original radar acquisition timestamps.

title: Regularize a time series of vertical profiles (vpts) on a regular time grid ‚Äî regularize_vpts
text: object class vpts regular time steps.

title: Regularize a time series of vertical profiles (vpts) on a regular time grid ‚Äî regularize_vpts
text: Projects objects class vpts regular time grid, fills temporal gaps nearest neighbor interpolation. Irregular time series profiles typically aligned regular time grid expected time interval radar provides data. Alignment performed using nearest neighbor interpolation limited neighboring profiles fall within +/- fill (centered) original profile. Remaining temporal gaps time series filled empty profiles values NA quantities, timestamp regular grid associated profile. plots regular time series (see plot.vpts()) temporal gaps missing profiles (e.g. due radar time) become visible, result gap filling empty profiles. irregular time series data points plot carried time series continues, temporal data gaps filled visually. keep_datetime TRUE original profile timestamps kept ts$datetime. may lead duplicate timestamps regularizing timegrid finer interval available profiles.

title: Regularize a time series of vertical profiles (vpts) on a regular time grid ‚Äî regularize_vpts
code: # start form example vpts object: data(example_vpts) ts <- example_vpts # data gaps are not visible: plot(ts) #> Warning: Irregular time-series: missing profiles will not be visible. Use 'regularize_vpts' to make time series regular.   # regularize the time series on a 5 minute interval grid tsRegular <- regularize_vpts(ts, interval = 300) # data gaps are visible: plot(tsRegular)   # regularize the time series on a 10 minute interval grid, # and fill data gaps smaller than 1 hour by nearest neighbor interpolation tsRegular <- regularize_vpts(ts, interval = 600, fill = 3600) # data gaps are smaller as a result of nearest neighbor interpolation: plot(tsRegular)

title: Calculate sunrise or sunset for a time and place ‚Äî sunrise_sunset
code: # sunrise in the Netherlands sunrise("2016-01-01", 5, 53) #> [1] "2016-01-01 07:58:17 UTC"  # sunset in the Netherlands sunset("2016-01-01", 5, 53) #> [1] "2016-01-01 15:28:31 UTC"  # civil twilight in Ithaca, NY sunrise("2016-01-01", -76.5, 42.4, elev = -6) #> [1] "2016-01-01 12:03:29 UTC"  # next sunset in South Dakota, USA sunset("2016-11-15", -98, 45) #> [1] "2016-11-15 22:58:56 UTC"  # Beware that some days have two sunsets, or # two sunrises! E.g. on 5 Oct (local timezone) at # this location  sunset is actually on the 6 Oct # in UTC time zone, i.e. the next day sunset("2016-10-5", -98, 45) #> [1] "2016-10-06 00:00:46 UTC" # One day later, sunset is again on 6 Oct: sunset("2016-10-6", -98, 45) #> [1] "2016-10-06 23:58:56 UTC"  # working in local time zones typically avoids such ambiguities: sunset(lubridate::as_datetime("2016-06-05",tz="America/Chicago"), -98, 45) #> [1] "2016-06-06 02:11:19 UTC" sunset(lubridate::as_datetime("2016-06-06",tz="America/Chicago"), -98, 45) #> [1] "2016-06-07 02:12:00 UTC"  # use force_tz to force output to a specific time zone, by default UTC: sunset(lubridate::as_datetime("2016-06-05",tz="America/Chicago"), -98, 45, force_tz=TRUE) #> [1] "2016-06-06 02:11:19 UTC" sunset(lubridate::as_datetime("2016-06-06",tz="America/Chicago"), -98, 45, force_tz=TRUE) #> [1] "2016-06-07 02:12:00 UTC"  # Also beware of jumps in sunrise and sunset date with longitude: sunrise("2016-11-01", 100, 45) #> [1] "2016-11-01 00:01:50 UTC" sunrise("2016-11-01", 102, 45) #> [1] "2016-10-31 23:53:50 UTC"  # Sunrise in the Netherlands sunrise("2016-01-01", 5, 53) #> [1] "2016-01-01 07:58:17 UTC"  # Sunset in the Netherlands sunset("2016-01-01", 5, 53) #> [1] "2016-01-01 15:28:31 UTC"  # Civil twilight in Ithaca, NY sunrise("2016-01-01", -76.5, 42.4, elev = -6) #> [1] "2016-01-01 12:03:29 UTC"  # Next sunset in South Dakota, USA sunset("2016-11-15", -98, 45) #> [1] "2016-11-15 22:58:56 UTC"  # Beware that some days have two sunsets, or two sunrises! E.g. on 5 Oct # (local timezone) at this location sunset is actually on the 6 Oct in UTC, # i.e. the next day sunset("2016-10-5", -98, 45) #> [1] "2016-10-06 00:00:46 UTC" # One day later, sunset is again on 6 Oct sunset("2016-10-6", -98, 45) #> [1] "2016-10-06 23:58:56 UTC"  # Working in local time zones typically avoids such ambiguities sunset(lubridate::as_datetime("2016-06-05", tz = "America/Chicago"), -98, 45) #> [1] "2016-06-06 02:11:19 UTC" sunset(lubridate::as_datetime("2016-06-06", tz = "America/Chicago"), -98, 45) #> [1] "2016-06-07 02:12:00 UTC"  # Use force_tz to force output to a specific time zone, by default UTC sunset(lubridate::as_datetime("2016-06-05", tz = "America/Chicago"), -98, 45, force_tz = TRUE) #> [1] "2016-06-06 02:11:19 UTC" sunset(lubridate::as_datetime("2016-06-06", tz = "America/Chicago"), -98, 45, force_tz = TRUE) #> [1] "2016-06-07 02:12:00 UTC"  # Also beware of jumps in sunrise and sunset date with longitude sunrise("2016-11-01", 100, 45) #> [1] "2016-11-01 00:01:50 UTC" sunrise("2016-11-01", 102, 45) #> [1] "2016-10-31 23:53:50 UTC"
